<P>
MORNING REPORT: LEGAL FILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAUNA SNOW, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A judge in Dublin, Ireland has waived a marijuana conviction for U2 member Adam 
Clayton, in exchange for the rock bassist's agreement to pay $34,500 to 
charity. Justice Desmond Windle discharged Clayton, 29, on Friday. Clayton was 
arrested Aug. 6 in the parking lot of a pub near his home. He admitted to 
possession of marijuana, and prosecutors later dropped a charge that he planned 
to supply the drug to others. Clayton, who was accompanied to the hearing by U2 
manager Paul McGuinness and drummer Larry Mullen, refused to speak to reporters 
outside the court. The fine will go to the Dublin Women's Aid and Refugee 
Center. SHAUNA SNOW 
</P>
